content.description: Climb overhanging arete on south side of boulder. Sit start on large holds on either side of arete. Move your way up large holds to top, slapping either side of the arete.
content.protection: 2 pads is good. Covers the rocks nicely.
content.location: The thin spine boulder directly behind Special K.

content.description: Climb face avoiding the seam, arete and right crack.  Sort of an eliminate, but tricky and fun.
content.location: Face just right around the corner from Special K.

content.description: Climb up face with cool moon shaped hold just to the right of Welcome Arete.  Nice warm up.
content.location: Face to the right of Welcome Arete.

content.description: Climb up crack to top.  Fun warm up.
content.location: Just to the right of the Welcome Crack.

content.description: The obvious crack between Welcome Chimney and Welcome Crack 2.
Climb up crack just right of Welcome to the Lake.  Really fun, and tricky.
content.location: Just right of Special K and Welcome to the Lake.

content.description: The Obvious Chimney in the Welcome Area.
content.location: To the right of Welcome Crack.

content.description: Climb up arete in between Welcome Crack 2 and Welcome Face.  A real balance act.
content.location: Arete 10ft right of Welcome Crack, and just right of Welcome Crack 2.

content.description: Climb up the arete, lots of heel hooking and a couple of crimps. Topout is a bit heady, crux is definitely high up. Landing isn't the best, didn't test it though, so it could be anything.
content.location: 25 ft south of Welcome to the Lake, on the arete right of "I Don't Know, B"

content.description: Special K climbs the arete on sidepulls and small holds to the top. I don't remember seeing any jugs. Seems borderline V0-V1.
14 Feet. Use everything. Avoid the mossy area on the extreme upper left part of the face. There are some large holds which I don't think are part of the climb.
Start low on a huge rail, work your way up with a mantle, find a sidepull, and topout with another mantle. That's right, two mantles on one route. Crack and face to the left are definitely off.
content.location: 25 ft south of Welcome to the Lake, just right of giant crack and Eubank's Lady Bits, the green line on the photo.

content.description: Start with small right hand and a left sidepull, pull up to a ledge, and mantle. From there it is jugs to the top.
content.location: 25 ft south of Welcome to the Lake, between the two large cracks. Just right of Confidence Booster.   Yellow line in the photo.

content.description: Follow the vertical seam, using big holds on either side. Head straight up, I would suggest avoiding the ledges to the left to keep the problem a little more interesting.
content.location: 25 ft south of Welcome to the Lake, to the left of the big cracks, so just left of Eubank's Lady Bits.

content.description:
Down the hill and off to the side of Big Bud lies another tall and scary highball. Although similar in aesthetic and height to the mega-classic, in comparison the climbing is sadly inferior.

 Big Dud is a much easier climb and the landing is much worse. Follow the juggy shelves up the prominent arete and dont fall. 

 This line has probably been soloed by many in the past. 

 If being up high excites you but pulling hard doesn't, this is the route for you!
content.location: North east of the old bathrooms, just left of the bathroom boulder
